00:20:50.750 --> 00:20:55.670
It is generally perceived the
Indigenous people's cultures

00:20:55.670 --> 00:20:59.710
and traditions are kept alive
through oral traditions,

00:20:59.710 --> 00:21:02.690
generation to generations
for thousands of years.

00:21:02.690 --> 00:21:04.070
When you think about
it, that's a lot

00:21:04.070 --> 00:21:07.380
of information to retain
and to share.

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:11.140
However, not all nations
use oral traditions.

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:16.290 position:56%
Some nations use birchbark to
capture their writing and there were

00:21:16.290 --> 00:21:21.250
and are other examples of written
language used by indigenous people.

00:21:21.250 --> 00:21:27.350
Between 1809 and 1821, Sequoyah,
also known as George Guess,

00:21:27.350 --> 00:21:30.990
created the Cherokee syllabary.

00:21:30.990 --> 00:21:34.510
Sequoyah, a Cherokee
silversmith, simply just wanted

00:21:34.510 --> 00:21:40.330
to write his own name like other
silversmith want to sign his work.

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:42.090
He first tried picture
graphs but found

00:21:42.090 --> 00:21:46.830
that this would have
required thousands of symbols.

00:21:46.830 --> 00:21:51.190
He designed a symbol for each
syllable in the Cherokee language.

00:21:51.190 --> 00:21:55.530
The Cherokee symbol, or the
Cherokee syllabary, whether written

00:21:55.530 --> 00:21:59.300
in Cherokee language came
into being in the late 1810s.

00:21:59.300 --> 00:22:03.390
And in 1828, the Cherokee Nation
adopted the Cherokee syllabary.

00:22:03.390 --> 00:22:07.970
And in 1911, the Smithsonian
preserved the language.

00:22:14.060 --> 00:22:17.190
<i>The Cherokee Phoenix </i>was the
first Native American newspaper,

00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:20.010
the first issue published
in English and Cherokee,

00:22:20.010 --> 00:22:27.260
using the Cherokee syllabary,
in February 21, 1980-28.

00:22:27.260 --> 00:22:31.410
Elias Boudinot was the first
Editor of <i>The Cherokee Phoenix </i>.

00:22:31.410 --> 00:22:34.160
He named <i>The Cherokee
Phoenix </i>as a symbol of renewal

00:22:34.160 --> 00:22:39.910
for the mythical bird that rose
to life from the ashes of fire.

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:43.340 position:56%
The Nation founded the paper to
gather support and help keep members

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:46.250
of the Cherokee Nation
united, informed.

00:22:46.250 --> 00:22:50.300
It was also a platform to
discuss political decisions

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:53.310
that would eventually result
in the Trail of Tears.

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:54.840
It was a part of a movement

00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:58.130
to help the Cherokee Nation
create self-governing institutions

00:22:58.130 --> 00:23:00.430
in the new capital of Echota.

00:23:06.200 --> 00:23:09.300
Other tribal nations beside
the Cherokee also started

00:23:09.300 --> 00:23:10.600
to print newspapers.

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:14.750
They include the Cherokee,
Chickasaw, Choctaw, and Creek,

00:23:14.750 --> 00:23:18.460
and were influenced by tribal
leaders, and gave an official voice

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:20.870
to the elders and leadership.

00:23:20.870 --> 00:23:22.990 position:56%
Most newspapers were tribally owned,

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:26.960
and few owned by individual
tribal members.

00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:32.110
In 1935, the second Native
American paper, <i>The Shawnee Sun </i>,

00:23:32.110 --> 00:23:35.360
was published both in
English and Shawnee,

00:23:35.360 --> 00:23:37.740
also using the English alphabet.

00:23:37.740 --> 00:23:41.970
It was suspended in 1838
and resumed in 1841.

00:23:48.130 --> 00:23:52.130
By 1858, there was a
<i>Chickasaw and Choctaw Herald </i>,

00:23:52.130 --> 00:23:57.310
and by the 1840s tribes were
investing in official papers.

00:23:57.310 --> 00:24:00.840
Both tribal papers and
native writers were active

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:03.030
through the 1850s.

00:24:03.030 --> 00:24:06.240
However, as the political
situation of tribes shifted to that

00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:09.340
of assimilation or allotment,

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:12.060
publishing had weakened
and declined.

00:24:12.060 --> 00:24:14.350
To this day, tribal officials

00:24:14.350 --> 00:24:18.470
or the tribal government usually
control tribal newspapers.

00:24:18.470 --> 00:24:21.460
And as you see on this slide, a
little bit history and timeline

00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:24.970
of the newspapers starting
from Sequoyah to the 2000s.

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:36.240
It's also important to mention
Myrta Eddleman was the first Native

00:24:36.240 --> 00:24:40.960
American woman to own
a mainstream newspaper.

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:47.300
In 1898, Myrta launched the
<i>Twin Territories </i>which focused

00:24:47.300 --> 00:24:50.970
on Tribal Indian Territory
in Oklahoma.

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:59.960
Myrta's sister, Ora Eddleman, later
became Reed, served as the Editor

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:02.290
and Chief Writer for
<i>Twin Territories </i>.

00:25:02.290 --> 00:25:08.210
Between 1900 and 1940, publishers
and editors supported assimilation,

00:25:08.210 --> 00:25:09.930
control most public -- I'm sorry.

00:25:09.930 --> 00:25:11.230
I'm going to repeat that.

00:25:11.230 --> 00:25:14.160
Between 1900 and 1940,
publishers and editors

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:17.330
who supported assimilation
controlled most publications.

00:25:17.330 --> 00:25:22.860
A number of tribal publications
were started during this period.

00:25:22.860 --> 00:25:29.520
A few of them are, <i>The
California Indian News </i>, 1935;

00:25:29.520 --> 00:25:33.870
<i>The Winnebago Chieftain</i>
, 1905, in Nebraska;

00:25:33.870 --> 00:25:38.190
<i>The Claremore State
Herald </i>, 1905, in Oklahoma;

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:43.970
<i>The Rossville Reporter</i>
, 1913, in Kansas.

00:25:52.040 --> 00:25:55.360
Now moving on to Native radio.

00:25:55.360 --> 00:25:58.490
KYUK was the first
Tribal radio station.

00:25:58.490 --> 00:26:02.640
It went on air in 1971,
followed by KDKB

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:07.010
in Pinehill, New Mexico in 1972.

00:26:07.010 --> 00:26:11.320
Forty-six years later,
in 2017, that has grown

00:26:11.320 --> 00:26:16.320
to approximately 59 tribal radio
stations across Indian Country.

00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:20.770
Native radio is a powerful network
of individuals and organizations

00:26:20.770 --> 00:26:23.700
that support and encourage
one another.

00:26:23.700 --> 00:26:26.790
Radio stations are
often owned and operated

00:26:26.790 --> 00:26:31.470
by Native American Indigenous
groups, many on tribal lands

00:26:31.470 --> 00:26:34.970
in tribal communities, and
also a few in urban areas.

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:40.990
Radio programs in series
are developed

00:26:40.990 --> 00:26:45.460
by Native producers focused
on Native issues and cultures.

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:47.680
Native [inaudible] is
significant to both Native

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:51.330
and non-Native audiences
for a number of reasons.

00:26:51.330 --> 00:26:54.210
It gives indigenous
communities a powerful voice

00:26:54.210 --> 00:26:56.330 position:56%
