00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:28.200
I'm really thrilled to be here
today to talk about the <i>Indians</i>

00:35:28.200 --> 00:35:30.780
<i>for Indians Hour Radio Program </i>.

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:34.840
It started on April 1 in
1941, and it was broadcast

00:35:34.840 --> 00:35:40.290
from the WNAD AM Station
right on the campus

00:35:40.290 --> 00:35:42.400
of the University of Oklahoma.

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:45.580
And from the very beginning
it was a very popular show.

00:35:45.580 --> 00:35:51.210 position:56%
It was the creation of Don Whistler,
who was a Sac and Fox Indian,

00:35:51.210 --> 00:35:55.950
and he was also Chief of
the Tribe at that time.

00:35:55.950 --> 00:36:00.420
He had been educated
in Sac and Fox Country.

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:02.600
He grew up in Sac and Fox Country.

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:06.210 position:56%
And then as a young man he
attended the University of Oklahoma.

00:36:06.210 --> 00:36:11.250
And then he also went to the
University of Pennsylvania

00:36:11.250 --> 00:36:14.960
and worked in the museum
as a curator and also

00:36:14.960 --> 00:36:17.630
as a lecturer and performer.

00:36:17.630 --> 00:36:20.180
And so these are a couple
of photographs of him

00:36:20.180 --> 00:36:22.150
from when he was a young man.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:25.160
And on the right, you see
him wearing a headdress

00:36:25.160 --> 00:36:28.680
which is not what Sac
and Fox warriors

00:36:28.680 --> 00:36:30.400
or chiefs traditionally wear.

00:36:30.400 --> 00:36:33.490
But he would wear it
during his performances.

00:36:33.490 --> 00:36:37.610
And he would -- whenever he
was lecturing to Boy Scouts

00:36:37.610 --> 00:36:43.110
and other groups in Pennsylvania,
he performed dances and songs

00:36:43.110 --> 00:36:46.100
from other tribes, not
just the Sac and Fox.

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:50.520
This photograph is
from later in life.

00:36:50.520 --> 00:36:53.960
And he's talking to one of
the anthropologists on campus

00:36:53.960 --> 00:36:56.340
at our Natural History Museum.

00:36:56.340 --> 00:37:00.340
And I think this photograph
is from about the same time

00:37:00.340 --> 00:37:04.280
that he would have started the
<i>Indians for Indians Hour </i>.

00:37:04.280 --> 00:37:05.920
And he was also its host

00:37:05.920 --> 00:37:12.630
for its first 10 years,
from 1941 through 1951.

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:16.290
And he invited Native Americans
from all over the state.

00:37:16.290 --> 00:37:20.680
He had a wide network evidently
-- in Central Oklahoma,

00:37:20.680 --> 00:37:24.480
in Western Oklahoma, and some
getting into the eastern part

00:37:24.480 --> 00:37:28.370 position:56%
of the state, but maybe not so
much, because there are a few tribes

00:37:28.370 --> 00:37:32.970
that really aren't well
represented in the radio show.

00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:36.330
It was broadcast on
Tuesday afternoons

00:37:36.330 --> 00:37:38.730
for half an hour at l o'clock.

00:37:38.730 --> 00:37:43.660
But it was called <i>Indians
for Indians Hour </i>popularly.

00:37:43.660 --> 00:37:45.860
So that's just the weekly schedule.

00:37:45.860 --> 00:37:50.170
This is a program schedule
from 1948.

00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:52.820
This one is also from 1948,

00:37:52.820 --> 00:37:55.710
and it talks about the
popularity of the show.

00:37:55.710 --> 00:37:58.600
It says, "More and more
Indians are finding <i>Indians</i>

00:37:58.600 --> 00:38:01.460
<i>for Indians </i>to be one
of their favorite series.

00:38:01.460 --> 00:38:06.040
The programs include real
Indian music, songs, and dances,

00:38:06.040 --> 00:38:09.700
presented by representatives of
tribes from all over the state.

00:38:09.700 --> 00:38:12.820
Don Whistler arranges for the
appearance of these groups and is

00:38:12.820 --> 00:38:15.030
in complete charge of the series."

00:38:15.030 --> 00:38:16.330
And he was.

00:38:16.330 --> 00:38:19.590
