And then did actually
open a museum in 1916.

01:03:03.020 --> 01:03:11.390
And his concept, as was sort of
the fashion of the day, I guess,

01:03:11.390 --> 01:03:15.520
was that Native Americans
were a dying people.

01:03:15.520 --> 01:03:25.360
They were going to be assimilated
into mainstream culture.

01:03:25.360 --> 01:03:29.580
All evidence of their
heritage would be obliterated,

01:03:29.580 --> 01:03:33.230
and it was up to wealthy
white people like him

01:03:33.230 --> 01:03:37.400
to collect the evidence
of their heritage

01:03:37.400 --> 01:03:39.820
and make it available
to other white scholars.

01:03:39.820 --> 01:03:43.120
And for decades, that's
how they proceeded.

01:03:43.120 --> 01:03:47.990
I think that one of the really
fascinating and maybe untold,

01:03:47.990 --> 01:03:52.010
or undertold parts of the
story of the National Museum

01:03:52.010 --> 01:03:53.960
of the American Indian
is that transformation

01:03:53.960 --> 01:03:57.400
from being an institution
largely for white people

01:03:57.400 --> 01:04:01.610
by white people intended
for, you know,

01:04:01.610 --> 01:04:08.060
sort of a colonialist audience, to
being an institution run largely

01:04:08.060 --> 01:04:14.360
by Native People, who conceives of
our audience and our constituency

01:04:14.360 --> 01:04:17.040
as being the Native People
of the Western Hemisphere,

01:04:17.040 --> 01:04:24.070
that we are an institution
dedicated to documenting the lives

01:04:24.070 --> 01:04:29.740
of the Native People of the Western
Hemisphere and largely in support

01:04:29.740 --> 01:04:31.450
of revitalizing those cultures,

01:04:31.450 --> 01:04:37.390
of making cultural heritage
available to community members.

01:04:37.390 --> 01:04:41.820
So we very much think of
ourselves as the stewards

01:04:41.820 --> 01:04:46.380
of the cultural heritage
of the Western Hemisphere.

01:04:46.380 --> 01:04:52.220
When George Gustav Heye began
the museum, and for many,

01:04:52.220 --> 01:04:57.810
many years after that, they
were really focused on this kind

01:04:57.810 --> 01:05:03.890 position:56%
of unrealistic idea that there was
sort of a perfect moment in the past

01:05:03.890 --> 01:05:07.700
that truly represented what Native
People's lives were really like,

01:05:07.700 --> 01:05:11.040
and that they were going to
collect and document that stuff.

01:05:11.040 --> 01:05:17.690
And so, for a long time, archival
materials were not really part

01:05:17.690 --> 01:05:21.880
of the picture because they were
looking for archeological materials

01:05:21.880 --> 01:05:26.240
or some sort of ethnographic
materials that met a kind

01:05:26.240 --> 01:05:32.270
of standard that they
as curators set.

01:05:32.270 --> 01:05:35.630
So our collections, our archival
collections, are not nearly

01:05:35.630 --> 01:05:41.930
as robust or as historical as
our material culture collections.

01:05:41.930 --> 01:05:45.920
And we also have the benefit of
being part of the Smithsonian

01:05:45.920 --> 01:05:48.240
which has the National
Anthropological Archive

01:05:48.240 --> 01:05:52.570 position:56%
which dates back to, you know, their
collections date back to the 1860s.

01:05:52.570 --> 01:05:55.130
So we don't try to collect
anthropological records.

01:05:55.130 --> 01:05:59.030
So in terms of the archives in
the Museum of the American Indian,

01:05:59.030 --> 01:06:03.720
we've kind of been
triangulating towards a niche.

01:06:03.720 --> 01:06:08.510
And that niche is that we
document the contemporary lives

01:06:08.510 --> 01:06:11.050
of the Native People of
the Western Hemisphere,

01:06:11.050 --> 01:06:19.800
and seek to demonstrate the
connections that people make,

01:06:19.800 --> 01:06:23.460
and the context that they're
contemporary lives have

01:06:23.460 --> 01:06:24.760
with their traditions.

01:06:24.760 --> 01:06:30.710
And so we do this by collecting
the personal papers of artists

01:06:30.710 --> 01:06:34.760
and writers and leaders
and activists,

01:06:34.760 --> 01:06:36.970
and the organizational records

01:06:36.970 --> 01:06:41.520
of Native American Civil
Rights Organizations

01:06:41.520 --> 01:06:44.320
such as the National Congress
of the American Indian.

01:06:44.320 --> 01:06:48.600
We have about 50 years
worth of their papers.

01:06:48.600 --> 01:06:55.460
So what I'm kind of
driving at is that we seek

01:06:55.460 --> 01:06:59.460
to contextualize people's
contemporary lives

01:06:59.460 --> 01:07:04.720
and how the traditions that
they have been raised in

01:07:04.720 --> 01:07:08.130
and the continuity of
Native culture informs those

01:07:08.130 --> 01:07:09.550
contemporary experiences.

01:07:09.550 --> 01:07:15.070
Well, radio is a really
great medium for that.

01:07:15.070 --> 01:07:18.100
It's interesting that I
learned about the <i>Indians</i>

01:07:18.100 --> 01:07:21.020
<i>for Indians Hour </i>because
one of our staff people,

01:07:21.020 --> 01:07:22.320
a man named Ed Shoopman
[assumed spelling],

01:07:22.320 --> 01:07:26.740
who runs our National
Education Initiative,

01:07:26.740 --> 01:07:29.370
used to work at the Library
of Congress in the 1970s,

01:07:29.370 --> 01:07:33.060
and I believe that he's the person
who might have been responsible

01:07:33.060 --> 01:07:38.870
for having the Library of Congress
preserve those acetate recordings,

01:07:38.870 --> 01:07:42.680
because he told me about going to
Oklahoma and hearing the <i>Indians</i>

01:07:42.680 --> 01:07:49.600
<i>for Indians Hour </i>, and -- I mean,
what a perfect example of how --

01:07:49.600 --> 01:07:52.680
if people throughout the world,

01:07:52.680 --> 01:07:54.060
and the Western Hemisphere's
no different,

01:07:54.060 --> 01:07:59.790
they've always used the technology
and the mediums at their disposal.

01:07:59.790 --> 01:08:01.450
This gets to what you
were talking about,

01:08:01.450 --> 01:08:04.970
about newspapers and broadcasting.

01:08:04.970 --> 01:08:12.390
So we do have collections
of media producers.

01:08:12.390 --> 01:08:14.130
We have, for instance, the records

01:08:14.130 --> 01:08:18.800 position:56%
of a really fabulous Native American
filmmaker and documentarian,

01:08:18.800 --> 01:08:25.870 position:56%
Phil Lucas, who made really
terrific programs in the late 1970s.

01:08:25.870 --> 01:08:30.300
He made a series of television
programs about the portrayal

01:08:30.300 --> 01:08:33.540
of Indians in Hollywood
and on television, and if,

01:08:33.540 --> 01:08:37.730
when you watch this, images on
Indians -- when you watch it today,

01:08:37.730 --> 01:08:42.910
it is exactly as current
and informative

01:08:42.910 --> 01:08:44.360
as it was when it was made.

01:08:44.360 --> 01:08:48.790
I mean, which is kind of a sad
statement about the progress

01:08:48.790 --> 01:08:53.620
that mainstream media has made
in representing Native People.

01:08:53.620 --> 01:08:57.210
But he did a really great job
of making a fantastic series

01:08:57.210 --> 01:08:59.120
of documentaries about that.

01:08:59.120 --> 01:09:04.410
The Museum of the American Indian
has made, as far as I am aware of,

01:09:04.410 --> 01:09:07.560
only one foray into radio
production ourselves.

01:09:07.560 --> 01:09:10.430
And it was in the late 1990s.

01:09:10.430 --> 01:09:12.380
I believe they were
published in 2001.

01:09:12.380 --> 01:09:14.910
It's a series called <i>Living
Voices </i>, and it was produced

01:09:14.910 --> 01:09:19.210
by two long-time staff
people, Elizabeth Weatherford,

01:09:19.210 --> 01:09:23.710
who just recently retired, but
for over 30 years ran our Film

01:09:23.710 --> 01:09:29.390 position:56%
and Video Public Program., and
Keevin Lewis, who also just retired.

01:09:29.390 --> 01:09:37.440
But Keevin ran a really great
program, bring Native artists

01:09:37.440 --> 01:09:43.320
into work with collections which
is just a really special thing

01:09:43.320 --> 01:09:44.620
about NMAI.

01:09:44.620 --> 01:09:47.740
It's one of the more gratifying
things about working there.

01:09:47.740 --> 01:09:53.350
So <i>Living Voices </i>was 40
Dort profiles of Native people

01:09:53.350 --> 01:09:57.160
and leaders, contemporary leaders.

01:09:57.160 --> 01:09:58.800
It's kind of assembled
from more than,

01:09:58.800 --> 01:10:00.250
